tarted-with-kubernetes-cluster-ci-cd-for-azure-kubernetes-service\/ \">Kubernetes cluster for beginner<\/a><\/strong><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<div class=\"ast-oembed-container\" style=\"height: 100%;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Deploy Docker image to Kubernetes Cluster | CI-CD for Azure Kubernetes Service\" width=\"500\" height=\"281\" src=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/embed\/4DUhc0MjdUc?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen><\/iframe><\/div>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>The process of setting and displaying a variable is described in more detail below.<\/p>\n<p>First, I\u00a0create\u00a0<strong>Command Line<\/strong> task to write my name, so I can recognize that part very quickly.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2018\/03\/11\/vsts-build-variables-and-echo\/creating-a-command-line-task-in-vsts\/\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-8333 size-large\" title=\"Creating a Command Line task in VSTS\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/03\/Creating-a-Command-Line-task-in-VSTS-1024x555.png\" alt=\"Creating a Command Line task in VSTS\" width=\"760\" height=\"412\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/03\/Creating-a-Command-Line-task-in-VSTS.png 1024w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/03\/Creating-a-Command-Line-task-in-VSTS-300x163.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/03\/Creating-a-Command-Line-task-in-VSTS-768x416.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 760px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>Then I\u00a0create the second <strong>Command Line<\/strong> to print out the value, remember the variable is <strong>$(var)<\/strong>, but since we use that with echo, &#8211; we will use <strong>%var%<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2018\/03\/11\/vsts-build-variables-and-echo\/vsts-command-line-task-print-out-the-value-of-a-variable\/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-8334\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-8334 size-large\" title=\"VSTS Command Line task - print out the value of a variable\" src=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/03\/VSTS-Command-Line-task-print-out-the-value-of-a-variable-1024x572.png\" alt=\"VSTS Command Line task - print out the value of a variable\" width=\"760\" height=\"425\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/03\/VSTS-Command-Line-task-print-out-the-value-of-a-variable.png 1024w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/03\/VSTS-Command-Line-task-print-out-the-value-of-a-variable-300x168.png 300w, https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/03\/VSTS-Command-Line-task-print-out-the-value-of-a-variable-768x429.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 760px) 100vw, 760px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<blockquote><p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Variable names are transformed to uppercase, and the characters &#8220;.&#8221; and &#8221; &#8221; are replaced by &#8220;_&#8221;.<\/p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">For example, <strong>Agent.WorkFolder<\/strong> becomes <strong>AGENT_WORKFOLDER<\/strong>. On <strong>Windows<\/strong>, you access this as <strong>%AGENT_WORKFOLDER<\/strong> or <strong>$env:AGENT_WORKFOLDER<\/strong>. On <strong>Linux<\/strong> and <strong>macOS.<\/strong> you use <strong>$AGENT_WORKFOLDER<\/strong>.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>In <strong>Ubuntu<\/strong> machine, it doesn&#8217;t include the full path with driver letter like <strong>Windows<\/strong><\/p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_8739\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-8739\" style=\"width: 760px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><a href=\"https:\/\/mohamedradwan.com\/2018\/03\/11\/vsts-build-variables-and-echo\/define-and-modify-your-variables-azure-devops-on-linux-and-